TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Preorder Strategy with Endogenous Information Control
AU  - Chu, Leon Yang
AU  - Zhang, Hao
Y1  - 2011/04/21
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2011/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1110.1335
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1110.1335
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1055
EP  - 1077
VL  - 57
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, we investigate the integrated information and pricing strategy for a seller who can take customer preorders before the release of a product. The preorder option enables the seller to sell a product at an early stage when consumers are less certain about their valuations. We find that the optimal pricing strategy may be highly dependent on the amount of information available at preorder and that a small change in the latter may cause a dramatic change in the proportion of consumers who preorder under optimal pricing. Furthermore, the seller's optimal information strategy depends on a key measure, the normalized margin, which is the ratio between the expected profit margin and the standard deviation of consumer valuation. Although the seller may want to release some information or none, she should never release all information. Finally, under the optimal information and pricing strategy, the benefit of preorder is most pronounced when the normalized margin is in a medium range. This paper was accepted by Martin Lariviere, operations management.
AB  - In this paper, we investigate the integrated information and pricing strategy for a seller who can take customer preorders before the release of a product. The preorder option enables the seller to sell a product at an early stage when consumers are less certain about their valuations. We find that the optimal pricing strategy may be highly dependent on the amount of information available at preorder and that a small change in the latter may cause a dramatic change in the proportion of consumers who preorder under optimal pricing. Furthermore, the seller's optimal information strategy depends on a key measure, the normalized margin, which is the ratio between the expected profit margin and the standard deviation of consumer valuation. Although the seller may want to release some information or none, she should never release all information. Finally, under the optimal information and pricing strategy, the benefit of preorder is most pronounced when the normalized margin is in a medium range. This paper was accepted by Martin Lariviere, operations management.
